    GermaParl (v1.1.0)

    Corpus Documentation

    Andreas Blaette (andreas.blaette@uni-due.de)

    2017-11-17

    A Corpus of Plenary Protocols

    Parliamentary debates convey the arguments, interpretations and contestations that shape political decision-making. They are recorded and transcribed by parliamentary administrations with diligence, and published as plenary protocols. These documents are available for long periods of time – for several decades and more – and they cover the full breadth of topics that is processed by a political system: Plenary protocols are a valuable resource for research on policy and politics.

    The digital availability of plenary protocols is excellent and limited at the same time. They can be downloaded without restrictions as txt or pdf documents, sometimes as html. But this does not match the requirements for digital-era data processing. The GermaParl corpus as it has been prepared in the PolMine Project intends to contribute to the broader development of making corpora of plenary protocols availale in a digital-era data fashion.

    The GermaParl Corpus (the naming of the corpus is inspired by the DutchParl corpus, see Marx & Schuth 2010) as published here includes all plenary protocols that were published by the German Bundestag between 1996 and 2013. Plain text documents issued by the German Bundestag were considered the best raw data format for corpus preparation and were used whenever they are available. For a period between 2008 and 2010, txt files are not available throughout. To fill the gap, pdf documents were processed.

    The GermaParl corpus is a corpus of the debates and speeches that were actually given in the German Bundestag. Speeches that were only included in the printed protocol are not yet part of corpus preparation. Using an automized pipeline, raw protocols (pdf and txt file format) were turned into an XML standard that is in line with the standards of the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI). The data included in this package builds on the TEI data, but it has been converted by some standard Natural Language Processing steps (tokenization, lemmatization, part-of-speech annotation) and imported into the Corpus Workbench (CWB).

    Corpus Preparation

    The preparation of the GermaParl corpus implements the following workflow:

    • Preprocessing: Prepare consolidated UTF-8 plain text documents (ensuring uniformity of encodings, conversion of pdf to txt if necessary);

    • XMLification: Turn the plain text documents into TEI format: Extraction of metadata, annotation of speakers etc.;

    • Consolidation: Consolidating speaker names and enriching documents.

    The preprocessing step is not as trivial as it might seem. Older plain text files are offered by the German Bundestag in all kinds of encodings that are out of use today. The pdf documents have a two-column layout that is difficult to handle. Experience to handle these issues is captured by the respective functionality that is included in the R package ctk.

    The essential instument for the XMLification is a set of regular expressions to extract relevant metadata (such as legislative period, session number or date), to find the beginning and the end of a debate, the call upon the speakers, and the beginning and end of agenda items. The matches are used to generate the structural annotation of parliamentary speech in the XML document. However, due to the remaining haphazard variations that occur in plenary protocols we found it futile to strive for the battery of regular expressions that would always work without manual interference. Even though it introduces an element of manual work, our solution is to work with lists of mismatches (matches of regular expressions to omit), in combination with a brute-force preprocessing (hard-coded substitutions) that correct obvious errors in the formatting of a plenary protocol.

    The result of the base XMLification still includes noise, particularly because of the inconsistencies that occur with names. All the information that has been extracted is checked (including approximate string matching) against an external data source. We opted for lists of members of parliamentarians, cabinet members and further speakers that are available on Wikipedia. This is not only because of the easy digital access. Wikipedia pages for the parliamentary sessions are being taken care of by a dedicated team of volunteers. Wikipedia pages are undergoing permanent public scrutiny, ensuring quality checks on the data quality in a manner traditional printed material does not necessarily ensure.

    The code for corpus preparation is wrapped in a R package, and upon preparing a corpus, the version number of the package used is included in the TEI metadata, so that the corpus preparation is fully transparent and reproducible.

    Annotation

    Linguistic Annotation

    The corpus as it has been imported into the Corpus Workbench has been processed with standard Natural Language Processing (NLP) tasks. Along with each token, the part of speech (POS) and the lemma is available. The tools used for tokenization and the tagging is the TreeTagger.

    The TreeTagger outpus #unknown# if it cannot successfully lemmatize a wordform. See the tables in the annex to learn about the unknown ratio in the corpus.

    An annotation of sentences or paragraphs is not included in this version of the corpus. An upcoming version of the data will implement this and further annotation layers.

    Metadata (structural annotation)

    When the TEI data format is prepared for the import into the Corpus Workbench, the XML structure is flattened. All passages of uninterrupted speech are tagged with metadata, or so-called structural attributes (s-attributes). Note that parliamentary speeches are often interrupted by interjections. The following table provides short explanations of the s-attributes that are present in the GermaParl corpus.

    s-attribute description values
    lp legislative period 13 to 18
    session session/protocol number 1 to 253
    src source material for data preparation txt or pdf
    url URL URL of the original document
    agenda_item agenda item number of the agenda item
    agenda_item_type type of agenda item debate/question_time/government_declaration/…
    date date of the session YYYY-MM-TT (e.g. ‘2013-06-28’)
    year year of the session 1996 to 2016
    interjection whether contribution is interjection TRUE/FALSE
    role role of the speaker presidency/mp/government/…
    speaker Name speaker name
    parliamentary_group Parliamentary group partliamentary group the speaker is affiliated with
    party Party party of the speaker

    Using the GermaParl corpus

    The CWB indexed version can be used with the Corpus Workbench itself, or with any tool that uses the CWB as a backend (such as CQPweb). Most decisions were made with an eye to using the GermaParl corpus with the polmineR package. Please consult the usual documents that accompany R packages (README, vignette, manual) to learn how to use polmineR for your work with the GermaParl corpus.

    • Please keep in mind that plenary protocols meticulously report interjections. To maintain the integrity of the original documents, interjections are annotated in the corpus. By using the s-attribute ‘interjection’ that assumes the values ‘TRUE’ or ‘FALSE’ you can limit your analysis to speech or interjections.

    • The s-attribute ‘parliamentary_group’ actually refers to the parliamentary group, ‘party’ refers to the party a speaker is a member of.

    Future versions of the vignette may offer a much more elaborate tutorial how to use GermaParl in conjunction with polmineR. At this stage, the general advice is that good research with the corpus of plenary protocols will require a sound understanding of parliamentary practice.
